04966nam a22008655i 9780674369962DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013940373  a(OCoLC)1037981518  a(OCoLC)1041981979  a(OCoLC)1046610718  a(OCoLC)1047000464  a(OCoLC)1049661511  a(OCoLC)1054880870  a97806743699627 a10.4159/harvard.97806743699622doi  a(DE-B1597)427264  a(OCoLC)900718315  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aGV1785.B3 7aBIO0050002bisacsh04a792.80921 aGuterl, Matthew Pratt, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJosephine Baker and the Rainbow Tribe /cMatthew Pratt Guterl. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (286 p.) :b30 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1. Too Busy to Die -- t2. No More Bananas -- t3. Citizen of the World -- t4. Southern Muse -- t5. Ambitious Assemblages -- t6. French Disney -- t7. Mother of a Wounded World -- t8. Unraveling Plots -- t9. Rainbow’s End -- tEpilogue -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCreating a sensation with her risqué nightclub act and strolls down the Champs Elysées, pet cheetah in tow, Josephine Baker lives on in popular memory as the banana-skirted siren of Jazz Age Paris. In Josephine Baker and the Rainbow Tribe, Matthew Pratt Guterl brings out a little known side of the celebrated personality, showing how her ambitions of later years were even more daring and subversive than the youthful exploits that made her the first African American superstar. Her performing days numbered, Baker settled down in a sixteenth-century chateau she named Les Milandes, in the south of France. Then, in 1953, she did something completely unexpected and, in the context of racially sensitive times, outrageous. Adopting twelve children from around the globe, she transformed her estate into a theme park, complete with rides, hotels, a collective farm, and singing and dancing. The main attraction was her Rainbow Tribe, the family of the future, which showcased children of all skin colors, nations, and religions living together in harmony. Les Milandes attracted an adoring public eager to spend money on a utopian vision, and to worship at the feet of Josephine, mother of the world. Alerting readers to some of the contradictions at the heart of the Rainbow Tribe project--its undertow of child exploitation and megalomania in particular--Guterl concludes that Baker was a serious and determined activist who believed she could make a positive difference by creating a family out of the troublesome material of race.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican American entertainers. 0aDancers. 0aFamilies. 0aTheater, Tanz. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Entertainment & Performing Arts.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2014z9783110370225oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067436996240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674369962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674369962.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11S